SIMPLE: web
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Web
<hw>Web</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>webbe</ets>, AS.
<ets>webba</ets>. See <er>Weave</er>.]</ety> <def>A weaver.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Web</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Web
<hw>Web</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>web</ets>, AS.
<ets>webb</ets>; akin to D. <ets>web</ets>, <ets>webbe</ets>, OHG.
<ets>weppi</ets>, G. <ets>gewebe</ets>, Icel. <ets>vefr</ets>, Sw.
<ets>v⟦aum⟧f</ets>, Dan. <ets>v⟦ae⟧v</ets>. See
<er>Weave</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is woven; a texture; textile fabric;
esp., something woven in a loom.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Penelope, for her Ulysses' sake,⟦br⟧
Devised a <qex>web</qex> her wooers to deceive.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not <qex>web</qex> might be woven, not a shuttle thrown, or
penalty of exile.</q> <rj><qau>Bancroft.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A whole piece of linen cloth as woven.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The texture of very fine thread spun by a spider for
catching insects at its prey; a cobweb.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The smallest
spider's <xex>web</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Fig.: Tissue; texture; complicated
fabrication.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The somber spirit of our forefathers, who wove their
<qex>web</qex> of life with hardly a . . . thread of rose-color or
gold.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such has been the perplexing ingenuity of commentators that it is
difficult to extricate the truth from the <qex>web</qex> of
conjectures.</q> <rj><qau>W. Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Carriages)</fld> <def>A band of webbing used to
regulate the extension of the hood.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A thin metal sheet, plate, or strip, as of
lead.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And Christians slain roll up in <qex>webs</qex> of lead.</q>
<rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>Specifically: -⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>The blade of a sword.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sword, whereof the <qex>web</qex> was steel,⟦br⟧
Pommel rich stone, hilt gold.</q> <rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>The blade of a saw.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>The thin, sharp part of a colter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>The bit of a key.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Mach. & Engin.)</fld> <def>A plate or thin portion,
continuous or perforated, connecting stiffening ribs or flanges, or
other parts of an object.</def> Specifically: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>The thin vertical plate or portion connecting the
upper and lower flanges of an lower flanges of an iron girder, rolled
beam, or railroad rail.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>A disk or solid construction serving, instead of
spokes, for connecting the rim and hub, in some kinds of car wheels,
sheaves, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>The arm of a crank between the shaft and the
wrist.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>The part of a blacksmith's anvil between the face
and the foot.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Pterygium; -- called also
<altname>webeye</altname>.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>The membrane which unites the
fingers or toes, either at their bases, as in man, or for a greater part
of their length, as in many water birds and amphibians.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The series of barbs implanted on
each side of the shaft of a feather, whether stiff and united together
by barbules, as in ordinary feathers, or soft and separate, as in downy
feathers. See <er>Feather</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1638 -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pin and web</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>two diseases
of the eye, caligo and pterygium; -- sometimes wrongly explained as one
disease. See <er>Pin</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 8, and <er>Web</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 8.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧He never yet had <xex>pinne</xex> or
<xex>webbe</xex>, his sight for to decay.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Gascoigne.</au> --
<col><b>Web member</b></col> <fld>(Engin.)</fld>, <cd>one of the braces
in a web system.</cd> -- <col><b>Web press</b></col>, <cd>a printing
press which takes paper from a roll instead of being fed with
sheets.</cd> -- <col><b>Web system</b></col> <fld>(Engin.)</fld>,
<cd>the system of braces connecting the flanges of a lattice girder,
post, or the like.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>web</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: web
<hw>web</hw> <pr>(w⟦ecr⟧b)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The <er>world-wide
web</er>; -- usually referred to as <altname>the
web</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Web</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Web
<hw>Web</hw> <pr>(w⟦ecr⟧b)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Webbed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Webbing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To unite or surround
with a web, or as if with a web; to envelop; to entangle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Webbed</ent>⟦br⟧
